==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fahrenheit
<hw>Fah"ren*heit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[G.]</ety>
<def>Conforming to the scale used by <person>Gabriel Daniel
<etsep>Fahrenheit</etsep></person> in the graduation of his thermometer;
of or relating to Fahrenheit's thermometric scale. Used as an
alternative to <contr>celsius</contr>.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos>
<def>The Fahrenheit thermometer or scale.</def></def2>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <col><b>Fahrenheit thermometer</b></col> is so
graduated that the freezing point of water is at 32 degrees above the
zero of its scale, and the boiling point at one atmosphere of pressure
is 212 degrees. It is commonly used in the United States and in
England.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Faience</ent>⟦br⟧
